                                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE.&#8212;<name type="person">Private <hi rend="italic">H. S. McC</hi>&#8212;&#8212;</name>, <name type="organization">Co. A, 4th Georgia
                                                                Regiment</name>, aged 27 years, was wounded at the battle
                                                                of <name type="BATTLE" key="257">Chancellorsville, Virginia</name>, <date type="injury" when="1863-05-03">May 3d, 1863</date>, by a
                                                  conoidal ball, which fractured the frontal bone
                                                  two inches above the internal canthus of the right
                                                  eye. The internal table was comminuted. He was
                                                  admitted into <name type="hospital" key="176">Lincoln Hospital</name>, Washington, on <date type="admit" when="1863-05-07">the 7th</date>, being rather stupid, but not complaining of
                                                  pain. These symptoms continued until the evening
                                                  of <date type="injury" when="1863-05-14">the 14th</date>, when he appeared to be in a comatose
                                                  condition, and began to pass his urine
                                                  involuntarily. On <date type="operation" when="1863-05-15">May 15th</date>, at four o'clock P. M.,
                                                  his skull was trephined, and the depressed
                                                  portions of the outer and fragments of the inner
                                                  table were removed, giving exit to a quantity of
                                                  fluid resembling pus in color and consistency. The
                                                  comatose condition was relieved by the operation,
                                                  but death supervened on <date type="death" when="1863-05-16">May 16th</date>. The
                                                  pathological specimen is No. 1125, Sect. I, A. M. M.  The vault of the cranium is trephined just
                                                  internally to the right frontal eminence. The
                                                  diameter of the opening is three-fourths of an
                                                  inch. The specimen and history were contributed by
                                                                <name type="person" key="246">Acting Assistant Surgeon H. M. Dean</name>.</p>
                                                
